<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Teaches Aspiring Computer Vision Researchers From Around the Country</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Courtney Gilmartin
		
		<span class="date">Aug. 14, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 345px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1522/en_US/shahfull.jpg" height="226" width="345"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Courtesy of UCF Marketing</p>
			
			<p>Mubarak Shah directs the Research Experience for Undergraduates program. He believes it is great exposure for students who want to excel in computer vision.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400410b373f88011bc2160054007004">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cdellert@mail.ucf.edu">Christine Dellert, UCF News & Information</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-2947</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://news.ucf.edu/UCFnews/www.our.ucf.edu/opportunities/reu.php">UCF's Research Experience for Undergraduates</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Ajay Chabra is developing a program to find individual screen shots in lengthy video. Steven Braeger wants to find a way to fix digital cameras&rsquo; un-natural color corrections.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
Chabra and Braeger are two of 11 students from across the country involved in the University of Central Florida&rsquo;s annual Research Experience for Undergraduates in Computer Vision, funded by the National Science Foundation. This year&rsquo;s group includes five students from UCF and six other undergraduates from schools such as the University of Florida, University of Southern California and Rice University.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
During the summer months, when most students are thinking about anything but schoolwork, UCF hosts Research Experience for Undergraduates (REU) programs in disciplines ranging from nanotechnology and machine learning to computer visioning and optics. The programs aim to encourage undergraduates to pursue research endeavors and graduate school. During the past two decades, nearly 200 undergraduates from schools all over the nation have taken part in the Computer Vision program, UCF&rsquo;s longest running &ndash; going on 21 years. Its participants have co-authored more than 60 research papers, and six are now faculty members at universities.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
During this summer&rsquo;s program, which ends Friday, Aug. 15, participants attended introductory computer vision classes and conducted research in UCF labs. Students are working individually on projects ranging from video retrieval to image enhancement to robotics.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
In the fall, they&rsquo;ll continue their research projects and gather together twice more during the school year to review and discuss their endeavors. By the end of the academic year, students must write a comprehensive report describing their project, and they can choose to submit their findings to a science paper or journal.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
Chabra, a junior at USC who is originally from Long Island, N.Y., is contributing to UCF&rsquo;s TRECVid project. TRECVid aims to solve the problem of locating specific segments of footage in long-running videos.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
According to Chabra, the UCF program has led him to consider future career paths in the industry and academia. Whatever he decides, Chabra said that &ldquo;after finishing up my undergraduate studies, I would definitely like to go to graduate school.&rdquo;<br />
&nbsp;<br />
Braeger, of Bowling Green, Ohio, is a junior at UCF who wants to better digital pictures&rsquo; quality by undoing correction effects produced by camera circuitry. <br />
&nbsp;<br />
&ldquo;We have several labs on campus, and I hope that the one that I am involved with will be able to benefit from a simple, quick way to take uncorrected images as easily as they take corrected images,&rdquo; Braeger said.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
Director Mubarak Shah believes that the Research Experience for Undergraduates program is great exposure for students who want to excel in the computer vision field.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
&ldquo;This program has contributed to science and engineering by exposing undergraduates to the excitement and challenge of research,&rdquo; Shah said. &ldquo;Due to that, roughly half of the students have gone on to graduate school.&rdquo;<br />
&nbsp;<br />
Professors Niels Lobo of the Department of Computer Science and Takis Kasparis of the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering are also coordinating the program. <br />
&nbsp;<br />
The National Science Foundation granted UCF $300,000 in 2006 to host the Research Experience for Undergraduates in Computer Vision program. Students work full time in the program and receive a $4,800 stipend, a travel and meal allowance and free housing for the summer. <br />
&nbsp;<br />
UCF&rsquo;s Computer Vision Lab has received more than $1.2 million from the NSF to encourage promising students&rsquo; interests in science for the past 21 years.&nbsp; <br />
&nbsp;<br />
To learn more about UCF's Research Experience for Undergraduates programs, go to <a href="http://www.our.ucf.edu/opportunities/reu.php">www.our.ucf.edu/opportunities/reu.php</a>.</p>
<p><hr />
</p>
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</strong> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 48,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
